Lam Kinh historical site is a center for worshiping the emperors of the Le Dynasty. It was among the largest worshiping centers in Vietnam (and possibly in Southeast Asia) during the thousand years of Vietnamese autonomy. It is also the eternal resting place of six emperors: Le Thai To, Le Thai Tong, Le Nhan Tong, Le Thanh Tong, Le Hien Tong and Le Tuc Tong, as well as two mother queens: Ngo Thi Ngoc Giao and Nguyen Thi Ngoc Huyen, and a princess, Thuy Hoa. The Lam Kinh Festival was first held after the death of Emperor Le Thai To in 1433. Today, on the 21st day, the death anniversary of Le Lai, who was at Le Thai To‚Äôs side during the Ming invasion and gave his life for the emperor, and the 22nd day, which is Le Thai To‚Äôs death anniversary, of the eighth lunar month, people in the region hold the Lam Kinh Festival to commemorate their ancestors as well as the victory of the Lam Son revolt.
